<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-trig-evaluating" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Evaluating Trigonometric Functions</title>

  <objectives>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          Evaluate trigonomtric functions using special triangles.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Evaluate trigonomtric functions using the coordinate system and the unit circle.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Evaluate trigonomtric functions using graphs.
        </p>
      </li>
            <li>
        <p>
          Choose an appropriate method to evaluate a trigonomtric function at a given angle.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>
   
  <assemblage><title>Where will this be used in calculus?</title>
   <p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          Whenever trigonometric functions are used, it may also be useful to be able to evaluate them. 
          See <xref ref="sec-trig-intro"/> for some notes on where trigonometric functions are used in calculus.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          One specific example is when dealing with definite integrals that involve a trigonometric integrand.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </p>
  </assemblage>

  <introduction>
    <p>    
In this section we review methods for evaluating all six trigonomtric functions at given angles. Which method to use depends on the type of angle that is given. 
    </p>
  </introduction>

  
  <subsection xml:id="sec-trig-special"><title>Evaluating Using Special Triangles</title>
  <p> 
    Being able to evaluate trigonometric functions for common angles will be important in many contexts and examples in calculus. There are several ways to do this. One of the easest is to start with two special triangles.   
  </p>

  <!-- 
        <figure>
            <caption><m>\pi/4, \pi/4</m> special triangle</caption>
             <title>Special triangle</title>
            <image source="images/trigintro1" width="50%">
                <shortdescription>Special triangle, <m>\pi/4, \pi/4</m>.</shortdescription>
            </image>
        </figure>

        <figure>
            <caption><m>\pi/3, \pi/6</m> special triangle</caption>
            <title>Special triangle</title>
            <image source="images/trigintro2" width="50%">
                <shortdescription>Special triangle, <m>\pi/3, \pi/6</m>.</shortdescription>
            </image>
        </figure>
-->

<figure xml:id="fig-special">
    <caption>The two special triangles</caption>
    <title>Two special triangles</title><idx>Special triangles</idx>
    <sidebyside>
        <figure>
            <caption><m>\pi/4, \pi/4</m> special triangle</caption>
            <image source="images/trigintro1" width="10%">
                <shortdescription>Special triangle, <m>\pi/4, \pi/4</m>.</shortdescription>
            </image>
        </figure>
        <figure>
            <caption><m>\pi/3, \pi/6</m> special triangle</caption>
            <image source="images/trigintro2" width="50%">
                <shortdescription>Special triangle, <m>\pi/3, \pi/6</m>.</shortdescription>
            </image>
        </figure>
    </sidebyside>
</figure>

   <aside>
    <p>
      <alert> Study tip: </alert>
    </p>
    <p>  
      You should take the time to memorize these two special triangles if you haven't already. They will be useful in finding many trigonometric values. You should practice drawing them on a blank piece of paper until you know them.  
    </p>
  </aside>

  <example xml:id="trig-intro-ex1"><title>Evaluate using special triangles</title>
	<statement>
      Use the special triangles to find the value of <m> \cos \left(\frac{\pi}{3}\right) </m>.
	</statement>
	<answer>
	  <p>
		<me>
			\boxed{\cos \left(\frac{\pi}{3}\right)= \frac{1}{2}}
		</me>
	  </p>
	</answer>
	<solution>
		<p>
			We use the special triangle that has the angle <m> \frac{\pi}{3} </m>. 
      We also know from the definition of <m> \cos \theta </m> that <m> \cos \theta = </m> adjacent / hypothenuse. 
      Reading off the values in the special triangle we see that 
		</p>
		<me>
			\cos \left(\frac{\pi}{3}\right) = \frac{adj}{hyp} = \frac{1}{2}
		</me>			
		<p>
			The final result is:
		</p>
		<me>
			\boxed{\cos \left(\frac{\pi}{3}\right)= \frac{1}{2}}
		</me>
	</solution>
  </example>

  <exercise><title>Evaluate using special triangles 1 - HOMEMADE</title>
  <webwork>
    <pg-code>
      Context("Fraction");

      $a = random(2,9,1);
      $ans1 = Compute("sqrt(3)/2")->with(
               tolType => 'absolute',
               tolerance => .000000000000000000001,   );
      $ans2 = Compute("1/sqrt(2)")->with(
               tolType => 'absolute',
               tolerance => .00000000001,   );
      $ans3 = Compute("sqrt(3)/2")->with(
               tolType => 'absolute',
               tolerance => .000000000000000000001,   );

         Context()->functions->disable('All');
         Context()->functions->enable('sqrt');
    </pg-code>

    <statement>
      <p>Use the special triangles to find the following values. Answer in exact form (using square roots if needed). </p>
      <p> (a) <m> \cos \left(\frac{\pi}{6}\right) =</m>  <var name="$ans1" width="6"/>.</p>
      <p> (b) <m> \cos \left(\frac{\pi}{4}\right) =</m>  <var name="$ans2" width="6"/>.</p>
      <p> (c) <m> \sin \left(\frac{\pi}{3}\right) =</m>  <var name="$ans3" width="6"/>.</p>
    </statement>
  </webwork>
</exercise>

