      <p> (a) <m> \sin \left(-\frac{5\pi}{6}\right) =</m>  <var name="$ans1" width="10"/>.</p>
      <p> (b) <m> \cos \left(-\frac{5\pi}{6}\right) =</m>  <var name="$ans2" width="10"/>.</p>
      <p> (c) <m> \cot \left(-\frac{5\pi}{6}\right) =</m>  <var name="$ans3" width="10"/>.</p>
      <p> (d) <m> \csc \left(-\frac{5\pi}{6}\right) =</m>  <var name="$ans4" width="10"/>.</p>
    </statement>
  </webwork>
</exercise>

  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="sec-trig-right"><title>Evaluating at <m>0, \pi/2, \pi</m> etc. </title>
  <p> If you know the graphs of <m>y=\sin \theta</m> and <m>y=\cos \theta</m>, then it is easy to find the values of all trigonometric functions for any multiple of <m>\frac{\pi}{2}</m>. 
  Trigonometic graphs are discussed in <xref ref="sec-trig-graphs" />, but the graphs of <m>y=\sin \theta</m> and <m>y=\cos \theta</m> are also given here for convenience:
   </p>

  <aside>
    <p>
      <alert> Study tip: </alert>
    </p>
    <p>  
      You should memorize these graphs, and the graph of <m>y=\tan \theta</m>. A lot of information can be seen quickly in a graph, and for most people it's easier to memorize a graph than a long list of facts. 
    </p>
  </aside>

<figure>
  <caption>Graph of <m>y=\sin \theta</m></caption>
  <title>Graph of <m>y=\sin \theta</m></title>
  <image source="images/trig1sin" width="70%">
      <shortdescription>
          Graph of <m>y=\sin \theta</m>.
        </shortdescription>
  </image>
</figure>

<figure>
  <caption>Graph of <m>y=\cos \theta</m></caption>
  <title>Graph of <m>y=\cos \theta</m></title>
  <image source="images/trig1cos" width="70%">
      <shortdescription>
          Graph of <m>y=\cos \theta</m>.
        </shortdescription>
  </image>
</figure>

 <example xml:id="trig-intro-ex2"><title>Evaluate <m>\cos \left(\frac{3\pi}{2}\right)</m> </title>
	<statement>
      Evaluate <m> \cos \left(\frac{3\pi}{2}\right) </m> without using a calculator.
	</statement>
	<answer>
	  <p>
		<me>
			\boxed{\cos \left(\frac{3\pi}{2}\right)= 0}
		</me>
	  </p>
	</answer>
  	<solution>
	  <p>Option 1: Looking at the graph of <m>y=\cos \theta</m>, we see that at <m>\frac{3\pi}{2}</m>, the graph crosses the horizontal axis. Therefore the value is <m>0</m>. 
		<me>
			\boxed{\cos \left(\frac{3\pi}{2}\right)= 0}
		</me>
    Option 2: Another option would be to look at angles on the unit circle (in standard position, see <xref ref="fig-trig-intro1"/>). 
    	  </p>
    <image source="images/trig1ex5" width="70%">
      <shortdescription>
          The angle <m>\theta= \frac{3\pi}{2}</m>.
        </shortdescription>
  </image>

    <p>
    From the figure we see that for the angle <m>\theta =\frac{3\pi}{2}</m>, we have <m>x=0</m>, <m>y=-1</m> and <m>r=1</m> (<m>r</m> is always 1 on the unit circle). Also, <m>y=\cos \theta = \frac{x}{r}</m> (recall from <xref ref="trig-def" />). This means <m>y=\cos \left(\frac{3\pi}{2}\right) = \frac{0}{1}= 0</m>.
		<me>
			\boxed{\cos \left(\frac{3\pi}{2}\right)= 0}
		</me>
	  </p>
	</solution>
  </example>

 <example xml:id="trig-intro-ex3"><title>Evaluate <m>\sec \left(4\pi\right)</m> </title>
	<statement>
      Evaluate <m> \sec \left(4\pi\right)</m> without using a calculator.
	</statement>
	<answer>
	  <p>
		<me>
			\boxed{\sec (4\pi)= 1}
		</me>
	  </p>
	</answer>
  <solution>
	  <p>
		We know that <m>\sec \theta = \frac{1}{\cos \theta}</m> so therefore <m>\sec \left(4\pi\right) = \frac{1}{\cos \left(4\pi\right)}</m>. We can evaluate <m>\cos (4\pi)</m> by looking at the graph of <m>\cos \theta</m>, or by using the unit circle. Either way, <m>\cos (4\pi)=1</m>. Therefore <m>\sec \left(4\pi\right) = \frac{1}{\cos \left(4\pi\right)} = \frac{1}{1} = 1</m>.
	  <me>
			\boxed{\sec (4\pi)= 1}
		</me>
    </p>
	</solution>
  </example>
    
<exercise><title>Evaluate <m>\sin \left(\frac{3\pi}{2}\right)</m> - HOMEMADE </title>
  <webwork>
    <statement>
      <p>Evaluate <m>\sin \left(\frac{3\pi}{2}\right)</m> without using a calculator.</p>
        <p><m>\sin \left(\frac{3\pi}{2}\right)=</m><var name="'-1'" width="5" /></p>
    </statement>
  </webwork>
</exercise>

<exercise><title>Evaluate sine at multiples of <m>\frac{\pi}{2}</m>  - HOMEMADE</title>
  <webwork>
    <pg-code>
      Context("LimitedNumeric");
      $a = Compute(random(-9, 12, 1));
      $b = $a/2;
      $ans = sin(pi*$a/2);
    </pg-code>

    <statement>
      <p>Evaluate <m>\sin \left(<var name="$b"/>\pi\right)</m> without using a calculator.</p>
      <p><m>\sin \left(<var name="$b"/>\pi\right) =</m>  <var name="$ans" width="6"/>.</p>
    </statement>

  </webwork>
</exercise>

<exercise><title>Evaluate trig at multiples of <m>\frac{\pi}{2}</m> - HOMEMADE - NOW SHOULD ACCEPT DNE... CHECK VERY CAREFULLY</title>
  <webwork>
    <pg-code>
      Context("Numeric");

      $a = Compute(random(-12, 15, 1));
      $b = $a/2;
      $r = $a % 4;

      if ($r == 0) {
      $ans1 = num_cmp(0);
    } elsif ($r == 1) {
      $ans1 = str_cmp("DNE");
    } elsif ($r == 2) {
      $ans1 = num_cmp(0);
    } else {
      $ans1 = str_cmp("DNE");
    }  
      if ($r == 0) {
      $ans2 = str_cmp("DNE");
    } elsif ($r == 1) {
      $ans2 = num_cmp(0);
    } elsif ($r == 2) {
      $ans2 = str_cmp("DNE");
    } else {
      $ans2 = num_cmp(0);
    } 
      if ($r == 0) {
      $ans3 = num_cmp(0);
    } elsif ($r == 1) {
      $ans3 = num_cmp(1);
    } elsif ($r == 2) {
      $ans3 = num_cmp(0);
    } else {
      $ans3 = num_cmp(-1);
    } 
      if ($r == 0 || $r == 2) {
      $ans4 = str_cmp("DNE");
    } elsif ($r == 1) {
      $ans4 = num_cmp(1);
    } else {
      $ans4 = num_cmp(-1);
    } 
     if ($r == 0) {
      $ans5 = num_cmp(1);
    } elsif ($r == 1) {
      $ans5 = num_cmp(0);
    } elsif ($r == 2) {
      $ans5 = num_cmp(-1);
    } else {
      $ans5 = num_cmp(0);
    }
     if ($r == 1 || $r == 3) {
      $ans6 = str_cmp("DNE");
    } elsif ($r == 0) {
      $ans6 = num_cmp(1);
    } else {
      $ans6 = num_cmp(-1);
    }   
    </pg-code>

    <statement>
         <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
          <m>\tan \left(<var name="$b"/>\pi\right) =</m>  <var name="$ans1" width="10"/>.
      </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
      <m>\cot \left(<var name="$b"/>\pi\right) =</m>  <var name="$ans2" width="10"/>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
           <m>\sin \left(<var name="$b"/>\pi\right) =</m>  <var name="$ans3" width="10"/>.
          </p>
        </li>   
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\csc \left(<var name="$b"/>\pi\right) =</m>  <var name="$ans4" width="10"/>.
          </p>
        </li> 
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\cos \left(<var name="$b"/>\pi\right) =</m>  <var name="$ans5" width="10"/>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\sec \left(<var name="$b"/>\pi\right) =</m>  <var name="$ans6" width="10"/>.
          </p>
        </li>        
      </ol>      
    </statement>
  </webwork>
</exercise>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="sec-trig-summary"><title>Summary</title>
  <p> 
    The common angles we have evaluated trigonometric functions at, are summarized here.    
  </p>

 <assemblage xml:id="trig-common">
    <title>Common angles</title>
    <p>
      You should be able to evaluate all six trigonometric functions at the following common angles: 
    </p>
    <p>
    <ul>
        <li>
        <p>
          First quadrant: <m>\frac{\pi}{6}, \frac{\pi}{4}, \frac{\pi}{3} </m> (<xref ref="sec-trig-special" />)
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Corresponding angles in other quadrants, such as <m>\frac{5\pi}{6}, \frac{3\pi}{4}, \frac{5\pi}{3}, </m> etc. (<xref ref="sec-trig-circle" />)
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Multiples of <m>\frac{\pi}{2}</m>, such as <m>0, \frac{\pi}{2}, \pi, \frac{3\pi}{2}, 2\pi, 3\pi </m> etc. (<xref ref="sec-trig-right" />)
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Similar negative angles, such as <m>-\frac{\pi}{6}, -\frac{\pi}{2}, -\frac{3\pi}{4} </m> etc. (<xref ref="sec-trig-circle" /> and <xref ref="sec-trig-right" />) 
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </p>
  </assemblage> 
</subsection>

<exercises><title>Recommended Exercises</title>
    <p>
      For students who want a focused review of the topic, we recommend working on these exercises. 
      If you find that you want even more practice, there are additional exercises below. 
      If you find the Recommended Exercises difficult at first, you may want to start with the "Additional Exercises" (<xref ref="trig-eval-additional"/>) and then come back to the Recommended Exercises.
    </p>
  
<exercise><title>Evaluate at common angles - HOMEMADE</title>
   <introduction>
    <p>
       (Not randomized.)
    </p>
   </introduction>
<webwork>
    <pg-code>
      Context("Fraction");

      $ans1 = Compute("1/sqrt(2)")->with(
               tolType => 'absolute',
               tolerance => .00000000001,   );
      $ans2 = Compute("sqrt(3)")->with(
               tolType => 'absolute',
               tolerance => .000000000000000000001,   );
      $ans3 = Compute("2")->with(
               tolType => 'absolute',
               tolerance => .000000000000000000001,   );

         Context()->functions->disable('All');
         Context()->functions->enable('sqrt');
    </pg-code>

    <statement>
      <p>Evaluate the following without using a calculator. Use one of the techniques discussed in this section, as appropriate. </p>
      <p> (a) <m> \sin \left(\frac{\pi}{4}\right) =</m>  <var name="$ans1" width="10"/>.</p>
      <p> (b) <m> \tan \left(\frac{\pi}{3}\right) =</m>  <var name="$ans2" width="10"/>.</p>
      <p> (c) <m> \sec \left(\frac{\pi}{6}\right) =</m>  <var name="$ans3" width="10"/>.</p>
    </statement>
  </webwork>
  </exercise>

<exercise><title>Evaluate at <m>-\frac{\pi}{3}</m> - HOMEMADE</title>
   <introduction>
    <p>
       (Not randomized.)
    </p>
   </introduction>
<webwork>
    <pg-code>
      Context("Fraction");

      $ans1 = Compute("-sqrt(3)/2")->with(
               tolType => 'absolute',
               tolerance => .000000000000000000001,   );
      $ans2 = Compute("-sqrt(3)")->with(
               tolType => 'absolute',
               tolerance => .000000000000000000001,   );

         Context()->functions->disable('All');
         Context()->functions->enable('sqrt');
    </pg-code>

    <statement>
      <p>Evaluate the following without using a calculator. Use one of the techniques discussed in this section, as appropriate. </p>
      <p> (a) <m> \sin \left(-\frac{\pi}{3}\right) =</m>  <var name="$ans1" width="10"/>.</p>
      <p> (b) <m> \tan \left(-\frac{\pi}{3}\right) =</m>  <var name="$ans2" width="10"/>.</p>
    </statement>
  </webwork>
  </exercise>

<exercise><title>Evaluate at <m>\frac{7\pi}{6}</m> - HOMEMADE</title>
   <introduction>
    <p>
       (Not randomized.)
    </p>
   </introduction>
<webwork>
    <pg-code>
      Context("Fraction");

      $ans1 = Compute("-sqrt(3)/2")->with(
               tolType => 'absolute',
               tolerance => .000000000000000000001,   );
      $ans2 = Compute("sqrt(3)")->with(
               tolType => 'absolute',
               tolerance => .000000000000000000001,   );

         Context()->functions->disable('All');
         Context()->functions->enable('sqrt');
    </pg-code>

    <statement>
       <p>Evaluate the following without using a calculator. Use one of the techniques discussed in this section, as appropriate. </p>
      <p> (a) <m> \cos \left(\frac{7\pi}{6}\right) =</m>  <var name="$ans1" width="10"/>.</p>
      <p> (b) <m> \cot \left(\frac{7\pi}{6}\right) =</m>  <var name="$ans2" width="10"/>.</p>
    </statement>
  </webwork>
  </exercise>

<exercise><title>Evaluate <m>\cos \theta </m> without a calculator - HOMEMADE</title>
   <introduction>
    <p>
       (Randomized.)
    </p>
   </introduction>
 <webwork>
    <pg-code>
      Context("Numeric");
      $a = Compute(random(-5, 11, 1));
      $b = $a/6;
      $ans = cos(pi*$a/6);
    </pg-code>

    <statement>
        <p>Evaluate the following without using a calculator. Use one of the techniques discussed in this section, as appropriate. </p>
      <p><m>\cos \left(\frac{<var name="$a"/>\pi}{6}\right) =</m>  <var name="$ans" width="6"/>.</p>
    </statement>

  </webwork>
  </exercise>

